statement.p:
If \bA is m\times n and \bB is n\times p, then the product \bA\bB is defined as

					\bA\mathbf{B} =
						\bA \begin{bmatrix}
						\mathbf{b}_1 \amp \mathbf{b}_2 \amp \cdots \amp \mathbf{b}_p
						\end{bmatrix}
						= \begin{bmatrix}
						\bA\mathbf{b}_1 \amp \bA\mathbf{b}_2 \amp \cdots \amp \bA\mathbf{b}_p
						\end{bmatrix}
				.

example.p:
Let

	\bA = \begin{bmatrix}
		1 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 2 \\ -3 \amp 1
		\end{bmatrix}, \qquad
		\mathbf{B} = \begin{bmatrix}
		2 \amp -1 \amp 0 \amp 4 \\ 1 \amp 1 \amp 3 \amp 2
		\end{bmatrix}
.  
Then 

	\bA\mathbf{B} \amp= \begin{bmatrix} 
		(1)(2) + (-1)(1) \amp (1)(-1) + (-1)(1) \amp (1)(0) + (-1)(3) \amp (1)(4) + (-1)(2) \\
		(0)(2) + (2)(1) \amp (0)(-1) + (2)(1) \amp (0)(0) + (2)(3) \amp (0)(4) + (2)(2) \\
		(-3)(2) + (1)(1) \amp (-3)(-1) + (1)(1) \amp (-3)(0) + (1)(3) \amp (-3)(4) + (1)(2)
		\end{bmatrix} 
	\amp = \begin{bmatrix}
				1 \amp -2 \amp -3 \amp 2 \\ 2 \amp 2 \amp 6 \amp 4 \\ -5 \amp 4 \amp 3 \amp -10
			\end{bmatrix}
.

   Observe that 

		\bA \begin{bmatrix} 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix} = 2 \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 0 \\ -3
			\end{bmatrix} + 1 \begin{bmatrix} -1 \\ 2 \\ 1 \end{bmatrix}
			= \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ 2 \\ -5 \end{bmatrix}
	, 
	and so on.

Suppose 

	\bA = 
	\begin{bmatrix} 
	0 \amp -2 \amp 4 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\ 0 \amp 3 \amp -6
	\end{bmatrix}
. 
The RREF of the augmented matrix [\bA,\bzero] is found to be 

		\bA = 
		\begin{bmatrix} 
		0 \amp 1 \amp -2 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0
		\end{bmatrix}
. 
(Note that row operations could never change the zeros in the augmented column.) Hence the only pivot column is column 2, and all solutions are of the form 

	\threevec{s}{2t}{t} = s \threevec{1}{0}{0} + t \threevec{0}{2}{1}
,
where s and t are arbitrary scalars. You can easily check that both of the constant vectors above are themselves homogeneous solutions.

statement.p:
The nullspacenullspace of a matrix \bA\in\Rmn{m}{n} is 				

	\null(\bA) = \{ \bx\in\Rn{n} : \bA\bx=\bzero \} 
.

The span of vectors \bx_1,\ldots,\bx_k is 

	\span(\bx_1,\ldots,\bx_k) = \{ c_1\bx_1+\cdots+c_k\bx_k : c_1,\ldots,c_k \in \mathbb{R} \}
.

example.p:
Suppose the RREF of a matrix ends with
\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
(i.e., an identity matrix). There are no free variables, and the only solution is \bx=[0,0,0]. Hence \null(\bA) = \{\bzero\}. This singleton set does not have a basis and is considered to have dimension zero.

subsection.p:
Even though a 2x2 inverse is easy, it's still not the most convenient way to solve a linear system. There is an even faster equivalent shortcut known as Cramer's Rule:

	 x_1 \amp = \frac{ \twodet{b_1}{a_{12}}{b_2}{a_{22}} }{ \det(\bA) }
	 x_2 \amp = \frac{ \twodet{a_{11}}{b_1}{a_{21}}{b_2} }{ \det(\bA) }   
.

statement.p:
For complex numbers w and z, 


|\bar{z}| = |z|

|wz| = |w|\cdot |z|

|w+z|\le |w| + |z| (triangle inequality)

\left| \frac{1}{z} \right| = \frac{1}{|z|}

\overline{wz}=\bar{w}\cdot \bar{z}

\overline{w+z}=\bar{w}+\bar{z}

\overline{\left(\frac{1}{z} \right)} = \frac{1}{\bar{z}}

|z|^2 = z\cdot \bar{z}

subsection.p:
You should be familiar with the idea of multiplicity for roots of a polynomial. We can factor a characteristic polynomial p to get 

	p(z) = (z-\lambda_1)^{m_1}(z-\lambda_2)^{m_2}\dots(z-\lambda_k)^{m_k}

for nonnegative integer exponents such that m_1+\cdots+m_k=n. These exponents are the mulitiplicites of the roots.

introduction.p:
Say \bA is n\times n, and that we write 

	\bA \bv_1 = \lambda_1 \bv_1, \;
	\bA \bv_2 = \lambda_2 \bv_2,\; \dots, \;
	\bA \bv_n = \lambda_n \bv_n
,
where \lambda_1,\lambda_2,\dots,\lambda_n are its eigenvalues (including multiplicities). Through some linear algebra magic, we can express this collection of equations more succinctly: 


			\begin{bmatrix} 
				\bA \bv_1 \amp \bA \bv_2 \amp \cdots \amp \bA \bv_n 
			\end{bmatrix} 
			\amp = 
			\begin{bmatrix} 
				\lambda_1\bv_1 \amp \lambda_2\bv_2 \amp \cdots \amp \lambda_n\bv_n 
			\end{bmatrix}

	\bA \begin{bmatrix} \bv_1 \amp \bv_2 \amp \cdots \amp \bv_n \end{bmatrix}            \amp = 
			\begin{bmatrix} \bv_1 \amp \bv_2 \amp \cdots \amp \bv_n \end{bmatrix} 
			\begin{bmatrix} \lambda_1 \amp 0 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \\
							0 \amp \lambda_2 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \\
							\amp \amp \ddots \amp \\
							0 \amp \cdots \amp 0 \amp \lambda_n
			\end{bmatrix}
	\bA \bV \amp = \bV \bD            
, 
where \bD is a diagonal matrix.

example.p:
Let's find a diagonalization of 

		\mathbf{A} =  \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 4 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix}
. 
We found the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of this guy in the previous section. We got \lambda_1=3 with \bv_1 = \twovec{1}{2}, and \lambda_2=-1 with \bv_2 =\twovec{1}{-2}. So we paint by numbers to get

		\mathbf{D} = \begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix}, \qquad \bV = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix}
. 
We "just" need to invert \bV; fortunately, we're only at 2\times 2, so this is a snap.

		\bV^{-1} = \frac{1}{-4} \begin{bmatrix} -2 \amp -1 \\ -2 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} 1/2 \amp 1/4 \\ 1/2 \amp -1/4 \end{bmatrix}
.  
Hence

		\mathbf{A} = \bV \mathbf{D} \bV^{-1} = 
		\begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 1 \\ 2 \amp -2 \end{bmatrix} 
		\begin{bmatrix} 3 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp -1 \end{bmatrix} 
		\begin{bmatrix} 1/2 \amp 1/4 \\ 1/2 \amp -1/4 \end{bmatrix}
.
